@node Introduction
@prev Main
@next SystemRequirements

@{b}INTRODUCTION...@{ub}

Welcome to Flix!  Another great little program written by me!  Flix displays a
small (11x33 pixels) window on your Workbench screen which opens up to show the
screens currently open on your system (only those user-defined in the config).
You simply click on one of them and that screen pops to the front!

   I know that there are loads of others out there that do exactly this, but I
wanted to write one myself.  I made it look nice as well :).


   @{b}FEATURES...@{ub}

   · Up to 50 screens are user-definable!

   · 198 images to choose from (more on the way!)

   · Uses a palette of your choice! (Set PALETTE_LOCATION tooltype)

   · Use Config and Gadget files from anywhere on your system!  (Set PATH
     tooltype)

   · Utilises those lovely ReqTools requesters

   · Extremely user-friendly

   · Returns ALL memory on exit
             ---
   · Uses about 0.01% CPU time!  (Isn't the AMIGA cool!)


   · THIS IS THE @{"»FULL« VERSION!" link CDSingleWare}

@endnode
@node SystemRequirements "What Do I Need?"
@prev Introduction
@next WhatDoIDo

@{b}SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS...@{ub}

· Any Amiga 2.04 and above

· The @{"ReqTools" link ReqTools} library

· Workbench palette in MWB colours (optional)


The program has been tested on the following:

· Amiga 1200 ROM 3.0 - Blizzard 1260/50MHz - 2MB Chip - 16MB Fast RAM
                     - 2MB Chip RAM
· Amiga 1200 ROM 3.1 - Blizzard 1260/50MHz - 2MB Chip - 16MB Fast RAM
                     - 2MB Chip RAM


If Flix doesn't work on your system, write me.  @{"Chris" link Address}

@endnode
@node WhatDoIDo "OK, So I've Got This Program, What Do I Do With It?"
@prev SystemRequirements
@next Graphics

@{b}WHAT DO I DO?...@{ub}

   A small window will appear on your Workbench screen with the word FLIX in
it.  Simply press this gadget to view all the user-defined screens available.
They each have their own 8-colour gadget (hence the palette feature).  Press
the appropriate gadget and that screen will pop to the front.  Press the FLIX
button again and the new window will close again (the FLIX button is like a
show/hide button).


   You can run Flix from the CLI if you want.  Just make sure you use 'Run
<>NIL: Flix' or it won't detach from the CLI until you quit Flix.  This method
WILL use the Flix.info file if available, therefore using the tooltypes
correctly.

@endnode
@node Graphics "Lovely Little Images And How To Use Them"
@prev WhatDoIDo
@next TheMenu

@{b}THE GRAPHICS...@{ub}

   The 'Flix.Gadgets' file included in this release contains 198 images for
the gadgets within Flix.  This file MUST be in the directory you set in the
PATH tooltype or you'll see an error.  They are in the MagicWB palette.  So my
apologies to anyone who doesn't use it.  It's really great!  For this reason
Flix looks smart on a WB screen which uses at least 8 colours.

   The PALETTE_LOCATION tooltype can be used to load a palette of your choice
instead of using the default.  Set this to NONE to disable this feature.

@endnode
@node TheMenu "Hold The Right Mouse Button Down And..."
@prev WhatDoIDo
@next Tooltypes

@{b}THE MENU...@{ub}

   NOTE: To activate the window, simply press and hold the left mouse button
over one of the gadgets, then move off the gadgets altogether and release the
mouse button.

   There is one menu accessible when the Flix window is activated.  It is
called 'Main'.  There are just three options available:

 Show/Hide - This will either show the screen gadgets, or hide the gadgets,
         depending on their current state.

 About - This shows a requester telling you who wrote it (that would be me ;)
         It also has a button to load the Guide file document that comes with
         this release.  The guide file will be loaded provided the path and
         filename you've entered into the @{"VIEWGUIDE tooltype" link Tooltypes} exist and that
         Flix_V1.0.Guide exists in the PATH tooltype directory.

 Quit - Duh ;)

@endnode
@node Tooltypes "Another great Amiga invention!"
@prev TheMenu
@next ConfigFile

@{b}TOOLTYPES...@{ub}

   Flix uses a number of tooltypes from its icon.  The icon MUST be called
Flix.info or Flix won't be able to find it!  There are ten tooltypes to use:

  · DONOTWAIT - Set this if you want to use Flix in your WBStartup
                [Default: already set]  (There are no parameters for DONOTWAIT)

  · GADGETS   - The number of screen gadgets to display.
                [Default: 1]

  · IMAGES    - The number of images supplied in this release.
                [Default: 198]  (Don't change this!)

  · WINDOWX   - The x-position of the FLIX button.  This button appears at the
                right of the screen gadgets, so you should enter a number as
                big as the number of screen gadgets x 33 + 11 (33 is the width
                of the gadgets, 11 is the width of the FLIX button).  Invalid
                values will display an error and default to the right of the
                screen.
                [Default: 629]

  · WINDOWY   - The y-position of the FLIX button.  Its height is 11 pixels, so
                you should enter a value in the range 1 to screenheight-11.
                [Default: 27]

  · PATH      - The location of all the Flix files.  You can have Flix in your
                WBStartup, for example, and have the programs files on a
                different partition!  Note that the trailing slash or colon IS
                necessary!
                [Default: Sys:WBStartup/]

  · PALETTE_LOCATION - The path AND filename of your palette file.  Flix will
                try to use your palette file to use your systems colours.
                [Default: ENVARC:Sys/Palette.ilbm]

  · AUTOCLOSE - Do you want Flix to close the screen gadgets window when you
                click on a screen gadget?  Set this to YES or NO.
                [Default: NO]

  · STARTUP   - Should Flix open the screen gadgets window when the program is
                started, or should the window stay closed?  Set this to OPEN or
                CLOSE.
                [Default: CLOSE]

  · VIEWGUIDE - Set this to the path and filename of your preferred guide file
                viewer so that you can view the documentation from the About
                requester.
                [Default: Sys:Utilities/MultiView]

@endnode
@node ConfigFile "The Configuration File"
@prev Tooltypes
@next Errors

@{b}THE CONFIG FILE...@{ub}

The Config file must be edited manually at the moment.  A prefs editor may be
written @{fg shine}if@{fg text} I get positive feedback on this program!  Anyway, it's set out like
this:

FLIX1.0CDH       - required to check if it is a valid Flix Config file
SCREENNAME       - the screen name to search for (see notes below)
###              - the image number in the Flix.Gadgets file (must be odd)
...
...              - the above two lines repeated for each subsequent gadget
END-CONFIG       - simply tells Flix to stop reading the file.  Also acts as an
                   error checker.  Don't remove this!

Notes:

   Unfortunately, as there is currently no preferences editor, you don't know
what all the images look like.  All I can say at the moment is experiment.  I
will get the prefs editor finished for the next release.  Sorry!


   When entering the image number to use, make sure that you put only ODD
numbers in the config file.  The odd numbered images are the ones that are
displayed before you press the gadget.  The even ones are those displayed once
you have pressed the gadget.  Putting even numbers in the config file will
produce some strange results!


   The screen name to search for is flexible in that, if you use a program
which has different screen names, e.g. "Blitz Basic 2.1" is the screen name for
Blitz, but it becomes "File -" when you load a file in.  Flix will only search
for whatever you put in the config file.  So, if you put 'File -' in the config
then Flix will search for a screen BEGINNING with 'File -'.  In this way, you
don't need to specify 'File - Example.BB2' as you may have loaded a different
file in!  Clear?  Example:

   Screen name                Criteria             Found?
   -----------                --------             ------
   File - Example.BB2         File -               YES
   File - Launcher_V1.5.BB2   File -               YES
   File - Example.BB2         File - Example.BB2   YES
   File - Launcher_V1.5.BB2   File - Example.BB2   NO!      Clear now?


   By entering incorrect details into the config file, you will see a variety
of error requesters.  Click @{"HERE" link Errors} to see a list of all possible errors.


   On a 640 pixel wide Workbench screen, you can fit 19 gadgets at WINDOWX=627.
50 gadgets can really only be used by those with their Workbench at least 1661
pixels wide!  In the @{"future" link Future}, there'll be the option for more than one row of
gadgets, but who has more than 50 screens open at once? (and who has enough
memory for 50 screens?)

@endnode
@node Errors "Ahh, errors everywhere, fear not, I'll squish the blighters!"
@prev ConfigFile
@next Future

@{b}ERRORS I MIGHT SEE...@{ub}

   All errors in Flix V1.0 are numbered, so if you get an error and you don't
really know what it means, look for that error number in this guide file for a
better description.  Hereafter, PATH refers to the directory entered into the
PATH tooltype.


01:'      Cannot Find ReqTools!
        Sorry, But Flix Needs The
    ReqTools Library By Nico Francois'

   Flix uses various ReqTools requesters to show you what's happening.  You
need the ReqTools library by Nico Francois in your LIBS: assign on startup.
Flix WILL NOT continue without it!


02:'Cannot Find Path Given In Tooltypes!'

   Flix was unable to confirm that the directory you have provided in the PATH
tooltype actually exists.  Try a different PATH to where the program files are
stored and try again.


03:' Couldn't Find Flix.Config File!
    Cannot Get Required Screen Details'

   Flix couldn't find the config file in PATH.  Without it, Flix cannot create
the necessary screen details and gadgets and so will not continue.


04:' Couldn't Read Flix.Config File!
    Cannot Get Required Screen Details'

   As above.  A possible solution may be to read-enable the file with:

   Protect Flix.Config +r


05:'Config File Is Corrupt!'

   The first line of the config file should be FLIX1.0CDH.  It should not be
changed AT ALL as Flix uses this to ensure that the correct file is read in.
Flix will not continue unless this is corrected.


06:'  Error In Config File!
    Expecting A Screen Name!
        Edit Your Config!   '

   You haven't supplied a screen name in one of your config file entries.  Edit
your config file and enter the correct name.


07:'    Error In Config File!
    Wasn't Expecting 'END-CONFIG'
         Check Your Config!      '

   Flix encountered the end of the config file before it had read in all of the
gadgets.  Check that there are the same number of screen entries as there are
gadgets.  Flix cannot continue until this is corrected.


08:'Invalid Image Number In Config File!
         Must Be Between 1 And 197
           Edit Your Config File!       '

   You have entered an image number outside of the supplied image file.  Please
change your config to reflect the correct value.  Flix will not continue until
you have corrected this.  197 is correct, even though there's 198 images.


09:'Couldn't Find Flix.Gadgets File!'

   There should be a file named 'Flix.Gadgets' in PATH.  You must have this
file in the correct place because Flix cannot continue without it!


10:'Too Many Gadgets For Current Workbench Screen Width!
            [1] Change Your Workbench Resolution
              [2] Reduce The Number Of Gadgets
                  [3] Edit Your Tooltypes               '

   Your config file suggests a number of gadgets too great to fit on your
current Workbench screen, ie. the width of the window plus your WINDOWX value
(in the tooltypes) would be too large.  To solve this, you can do three things:
(1) increase the size of your Workbench, (2) Reduce the number of gadgets so
that they'll fit on, or (3) edit the WINDOWX tooltype.


@{b}WARNNGS I MIGHT SEE...@{ub}

01:'    Couldn't Find Flix.info File!
      Cannot Get Tooltypes Information!
    Defaulting To Bottom Right Of Screen!'

   The Flix.info file wasn't found so Flix couldn't read the tooltypes to get
the window position or palette location.  Ensure that the file exists.


02:'  Invalid Value In 'IMAGES' Tooltype!
    There Were 198 Images With This Release
           Defaulting To IMAGES=198        '

   The number of images in this tooltype should ALWAYS be 198.  Flix will
default to 198.


03:'Invalid Value In 'GADGETS=' Tooltype!
          Must Be Between 1 And 50
           Defaulting To GADGETS=1       '

   You have entered a number outside the range of 1 and 50 for the number of
gadgets.  As this version of Flix can only accept up to 50 gadgets, it will
default to 1.


04:'Invalid Value In 'WINDOWX' Tooltype!
             Defaulting To XXX          '

   The WINDOWX tooltype in the icon holds a value outside the bounds of your
Workbench resolution.  Flix will default to as far to the right as it can.


05:'Invalid Value In 'WINDOWY' Tooltype!
             Defaulting To YYY          '

   As above, but for the Y-position of the window.


06:'Invalid Value In 'AUTOCLOSE' Tooltype!
              Defaulting To YES           '

   Flix was unable to find the desired value for AUTOCLOSE.  It will default to
YES (the screen gadgets window will close after flicking to another screen).


07:'Invalid Value In 'STARTUP' Tooltype!
            Defaulting To CLOSE         '

   Flix was unable to find the desired value for STARTUP.  It will now default
to CLOSE (the screen gadgets window will be closed on startup).


08:'Cannot Find Palette File Given In Tooltype!
          Unable To Use Specified Palette!     '

   The palette file given in the PALETTE_LOCATION tooltype doesn't exist!  Try
entering the correct path and filename and try again.


09:'Couldn't Find Flix_V1.0.Guide
               And/Or
       Sys:Utilities/MultiView   '   [Default: Sys:Utilities/MultiView]

   You used the 'Read Guide' button in the About requester to view the Flix
guide file that is included in this release, but it doesn't exist in PATH.  It
may be that you have renamed it.  It MUST be called Flix_V1.0.Guide.  Also,
whatever you entered into the 'VIEWGUIDE' tooltype must exist or the file
cannot be viewed.


10:' Couldn't Find Screen!
    Screen:<name of screen>'

   You tried to switch to a screen but it wasn't open!  You may have typed it
incorrectly in the config file.  Check that you've put the right screen name in
the config or try again when the screen has been opened.


   There is one more requester you'll see.  It's the Quit requester.  It simply
asks if you're sure you want to quit.  Click 'Yes' to quit, 'About' to see who
wrote this @{b}fantastic@{ub} program, or 'No!' to cancel.

@endnode
